2.1 Analyse de stabilité linéaire

Le premier énoncé sur le concept de stabilité pour les systèmes physiques a été formulé pendant le dix-neuvième siècle par James Clerk Maxwell, cité par Campbell & Garnett [3] (p. 440) :

"When the state of things is such that an inﬁnitely small variation of the present state will alter only by an inﬁnitely small quantity the state at some future time, the condition of the system, whether at rest or in motion, is said to be stable; but when an inﬁnitely small variation in the present state may bring about a ﬁnite diﬀerence in the state of the system in a ﬁnite time, the condition of the system is said to be unstable..."

